Experiences/Reflection:
Nearly every web-based application has a database of
some kind. There are hundreds of different databases, each
with their own benefits and drawbacks.
We use multiple databases so that they compliment each
others. This mitigates the drawbacks of each database.
Relational Database
• Stores data in tables called relations
• Examples: PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite
Document Database: MongoDB
Used to store web page data as JSON objects.
Building web pages become trivial.
Key-Value Database: Redis
Used as our key-value shard within our
sharding algorithm. Also used to cache
products
Graph Database: Neo4j
Stores products and users on the vertices. Edges
connect who bought which products. Performs our
recommendation algorithm in one, simple query.
Relational Database: PostgeSQL
Used to store permanent records of
transactions due to its rigid structure.
Normally, an application only contains one database,
chosen for it benefits to the project. However, as the
application and and features grow, the drawbacks of the
chosen database become more noticeable. So, how do we
prevent a database from failing to its drawbacks?
To demonstrate the use cases of multiple databases, we
built an ecommerce app. Where users can purchase
products. The databases will record users, products, and
transactions. Doing this, we can make each of the
architectures perform in the best way it can.
Polyglot databases are often used when a single database cannot support
your use case. Facebook uses 6 different databases in their architecture,
and many other tech giants use polyglot databases.
One downfall we saw during our development was the over-
complication of queries. When creating an object, we made 4 different
queries to our databases, each dependent on the previous one. Leading
to a messy chain of Promises — which is a JavaScript object used to
handle asynchronous actions, like queries.
Thanks to MongoDB, the frontend pages were easy and fast to set
up. Neo4J manages our purchase information and handles the algorithm
for recommending products. Redis, worked well as a cache, and to sync
up values, like incremental ID's between databases.
